kernel_variant.question:
Let (a_n)_{n\ge 1} and (b_n)_{n\ge 1} be real sequences that satisfy

a_1 = 3,\qquad b_1 = 4,\qquad b_n = b_{n-1} a_n - 5\quad (n \ge 2).

Assume further that

(i) the sequence (b_n) is bounded;
(ii) for every n \ge 1 we have b_n \neq 0 and b_n \neq -5;  (so all quotients that appear below are well defined);
(iii) b_n > 0 for every n.

Prove that the infinite series

S = \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{a_1 a_2 \cdots a_n}

converges and determine its value.
